Walden C. Rhines: Executive Profile & Biography - Bloomberg









































  





















































































July 22, 2017 9:47 AM ET
Software

Company Overview of Mentor Graphics Corporation



SnapshotPeople 




OverviewBoard MembersCommittees



Executive Profile
Walden C. Rhines  Chairman and President, Mentor Graphics CorporationAgeTotal Calculated CompensationThis person is connected to 5 Board Members in 5 different organizations across 6 different industries.See Board Relationships70$5,721,959As of Fiscal Year 2017
Background

		Dr. Walden C. Rhines, also known as Wally, has been the Chairman and President of Mentor Graphics Corporation since March 30, 2017. Dr. Rhines served as Chief Executive Officer at Mentor Graphics Corporation since October 1993 until March 30, 2017 and served as its Chairman since November 2000 until March 30, 2017. Dr. Rhines is a recognized spokesperson for the semiconductor and electronic design automation industries. He has 40-year history in the semiconductor industry. ... He served as Executive Vice President of Semiconductor Group and Vice President at Texas Instruments Inc. from 1987 to 1993. From 1985 to 1987, Dr. Rhines served as President of the Data Systems Group. He has experienced in high technology engineering and business management. During his 21 years at TI, he managed TI's thrust into digital signal processing and supervised that business from inception with the TMS 320 family of DSPs through growth to become the cornerstone of TI's semiconductor technology. He was also responsible for development of the first TI speech synthesis devices (used in "Speak & Spell"). He served as the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of 0-in Design Automation, Inc. since 2000. He served as the President of Mentor Graphics Corporation He managed TI’s thrust into digital signal processing and supervised that business from inception with the TMS 320 family of DSP’s through growth to become the cornerstone of TI’s semiconductor technology. He supervised the development of the first low-cost speech synthesis chips (used in Speak ‘n Spell) and is co-inventor of the GaN blue-violet light emitting diode (now important for low energy lighting). He joined TI in 1972 and held a variety of technical and business management positions, primarily in the Semiconductor Group, but also in the Consumer Products Division, Central Research Laboratories and Data Systems Group. Dr. Rhines served as the Chairman of Electronic Design Automation Consortium until June 1, 2012. He has been Vice Chairman of Electronic Design Automation Consortium since June 1, 2012. He has been an Independent Director at Qorvo, Inc. since January 1, 2015. He serves as Director of GlobalLogic Inc. He has been a Director of Mentor Graphics Corporation since October 1993. He serves a Board Member of both the Oregon Independent College Foundation. He serves as Trustee of Lewis & Clark College. He serves on the boards of the Semiconductor Research Corporation and the Oregon Engineering and Technology Industry Council. He served as a Director of Cirrus Logic Inc. from 1995 to July 2009. He served as Director of TriQuint Semiconductor Inc. since May 1995. He served as Director of 0-in Design Automation, Inc. He served as Independent Director of RF Micro Devices Inc. He served as board member of the Computer and Business Equipment Manufacturers' Association (CBEMA), and a Board Member of Sematech. He is co-inventor of the GaN blue-violet light emitting diode (now important for DVD players). He served as Chairman of the Semiconductor Technical Advisory Committee of the Department of Commerce. He served as an member of Executive Committee of Corporation for Open Systems. He earned a B.S. in metallurgical engineering from the University of Michigan, an M.S. and doctorate from Stanford University, an M.B.A. from Southern Methodist University and an honorary doctor of technology from Nottingham Trent University.Read Full Background




